SIMPLE: harmony
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Harmony
<hw>Har"mo*ny</hw> <pr>(h⟦aum⟧r"m⟦osl⟧*n⟦ycr⟧)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>;
<plu><it>pl.</it> <plw>Harmonies</plw> <pr>(-n⟦icr⟧z)</pr>.</plu>
<ety>[F. <ets>harmonie</ets>, L. <ets>harmonia</ets>, Gr.
<grk>"armoni`a</grk> joint, proportion, concord, fr. <grk>"armo`s</grk>
a fitting or joining. See <er>Article</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The
just adaptation of parts to each other, in any system or combination of
things, or in things intended to form a connected whole; such an
agreement between the different parts of a design or composition as to
produce unity of effect; <as>as, the <ex>harmony</ex> of the
universe</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Concord or agreement in facts, opinions, manners,
interests, etc.; good correspondence; peace and friendship; <as>as, good
citizens live in <ex>harmony</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A literary work which brings together or arranges
systematically parallel passages of historians respecting the same
events, and shows their agreement or consistency; <as>as, a
<ex>harmony</ex> of the Gospels</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Mus.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>A succession of
chords according to the rules of progression and modulation.</def>
<sd>(b)</sd> <def>The science which treats of their construction and
progression.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Ten thousand harps, that tuned⟦br⟧
Angelic <qex>harmonies</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <fld>(Anat.)</fld> <def>See <cref>Harmonic suture</cref>,
under <er>Harmonic</er>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><mcol><col><b>Close harmony</b></col>, <col><b>Dispersed
harmony</b></col></mcol>, <cd>etc. See under <er>Close</er>,
<er>Dispersed</er>, etc.</cd> -- <col><b>Harmony of the
spheres</b></col>. <cd>See <cref>Music of the spheres</cref>, under
<er>Music</er>.</cd></cs></p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- <er>Harmony</er>, <er>Melody</er>.</syn> <usage>
<xex>Harmony</xex> results from the concord of two or more strains or
sounds which differ in pitch and quality. <xex>Melody</xex> denotes the
pleasing alternation and variety of musical and measured sounds, as they
succeed each other in a single verse or strain.</usage>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 672 pr=JMD --></p>

<p><ent>Harmost</ent>⟦br⟧
